<Layout title="Ch 10: The Hypothesis Graph — Methodeutics" favicon="🔭">
  <main>
    <a href="/reading/methodeutics/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to methodeutics</a>

    <h1>The Hypothesis Graph</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Chapter 10 &middot; Kill conditions generate edges</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A monotone trend test fires but curvature is indeterminate. Is the system decelerating or drifting? You can&rsquo;t tell from the current data. But you know exactly what to run next: a longer experiment that resolves curvature. The failure mode named the next hypothesis. That is the edge-generation mechanism.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Chapter 9 classified trajectories into four bins: convergent, divergent, oscillatory, aperiodic. The classification works. Given a trajectory, you can assign a label. But a label is a noun, not a verb. It tells you what the system did. It does not tell you what to do next.</p>

    <p>The gap is between classification and generation. The reader who finishes Chapter 9 can look at a trajectory and say "oscillatory." The reader who finishes this chapter can look at a trajectory and say "oscillatory &mdash; test the interface between the two subsystems that are fighting." The label becomes an action. The mechanism is the kill condition.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>The central claim</h2>

    <p>The failure mode of a test names the next experiment.</p>

    <p>Every test in the classification tree either fires (assigns a label) or misfires (the data is ambiguous). When a test fires, you get a classification. When it misfires, you get something more valuable: a specific statement about what the data cannot resolve. That statement is a hypothesis. It points to the experiment that would resolve it.</p>

    <p>This is not metaphor. It is mechanism. The kill condition is a decision point where the test lacks the information to proceed. The shape of that lack &mdash; what the test needed and didn't have &mdash; specifies the next measurement. The failure mode is constructive. It builds the graph.</p>

    <h2>The kill-condition decision tree</h2>

    <p>Chapter 9 introduced the four bins. Here is the classifier as a decision tree, with each branch annotated by its failure mode.</p>

    <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 mb-4">
      <li class="mb-3"><strong>Test for monotone trend.</strong> Is the trajectory consistently increasing or decreasing? If it fails &mdash; no trend detected &mdash; skip to step 3 (periodicity).</li>
      <li class="mb-3"><strong>If monotone, test curvature.</strong> Is the rate of change decelerating (convergent) or constant/accelerating (divergent)?</li>
      <li class="mb-3"><strong>Test for spectral peaks.</strong> Does the frequency spectrum have a narrow peak? If yes &mdash; oscillatory.</li>
      <li class="mb-3"><strong>Test for aperiodic structure.</strong> Is there structure that isn't periodic? If yes &mdash; aperiodic.</li>
      <li class="mb-3"><strong>Nothing triggered.</strong> Null.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Five tests. Each test that fires produces a label. Each test that <em>misfires</em> produces a hypothesis &mdash; an edge pointing to an experiment that would resolve the ambiguity.</p>

    <h2>Misfires are edges</h2>

    <p>Three examples of misfires and the edges they generate.</p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Misfire</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">What the test needed</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 text-gray-400">Edge (next experiment)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Monotone trend detected, curvature indeterminate</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">More samples to distinguish deceleration from drift</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Run a longer experiment</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Spectral peak detected but broad</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Resolution to distinguish a noisy cycle from colored noise</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Test at a different frequency / longer window</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Nothing triggered</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Any detectable structure at all</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Test a different perturbation site</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>The first row is the opening example. The trend test fires: the trajectory is monotone. But the curvature test can't resolve whether the rate is decelerating (heading toward a fixed point) or constant (heading toward infinity). Both look the same in a short window. The failure mode &mdash; "insufficient samples to distinguish deceleration from drift" &mdash; names the remedy: collect more data. That is an edge in the hypothesis graph, pointing to a specific experiment with a specific expected outcome.</p>

    <p>The second row: the spectral test detects a peak, but the peak is broad. A narrow peak means a clean oscillation with a definite period. A broad peak means either a noisy cycle (the period exists but the signal is contaminated) or colored noise (no true period, just autocorrelation). The failure mode names two candidate hypotheses and the experiment that discriminates: sample at a different frequency, or extend the observation window until the peak either sharpens or dissolves.</p>

    <p>The third row: nothing triggered. The trajectory has no detectable monotone trend, no spectral peak, no aperiodic structure. Either the system genuinely has no response to this perturbation (a flat null &mdash; dead end) or you perturbed the wrong node. The edge points to a different perturbation site. This is the weakest edge &mdash; it says "try elsewhere" without specifying where &mdash; but it is still more than "fail to reject."</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>The classifications themselves generate edges</h2>

    <p>Misfires are not the only source of edges. A successful classification also generates hypotheses, because each label implies a structural claim about the system. That claim has consequences.</p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Classification</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">What it tells you</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 text-gray-400">What to try next</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Convergent</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Something absorbed the perturbation</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Test a different node &mdash; this one is stabilized</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Divergent</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">This is load-bearing, no backup</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Test what depends on it &mdash; find the blast radius</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Oscillatory</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Two subsystems are fighting</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Test the interface between them</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Aperiodic</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Input exceeds the architecture&rsquo;s capacity for structured response</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Decompose differently &mdash; the current partitioning is wrong</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>The convergent label says: something in the system compensated. The perturbation was absorbed. The next question is not "test this node harder" but "test a different node." The absorbing mechanism is working; the interesting structure is elsewhere. The label does not just describe. It redirects.</p>

    <p>The divergent label says: this node is load-bearing. Nothing compensated. The system's response grew without bound. The next question: what depends on this node? If it fails, what else fails? The edge points downstream.</p>

    <p>The oscillatory label says: two constraints are in conflict. The system alternates between satisfying one and violating the other. The next question: what is the interface between the two subsystems? The edge points to the coupling point, not to either subsystem individually.</p>

    <p>The aperiodic label says: the system's response has structure but no repeating pattern. The current decomposition cannot resolve it into periodic components. The next question: is there a different decomposition that would reveal structure? The edge points to the analyst's modeling choices, not to the system itself.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>The hypothesis graph</h2>

    <p>The kill-condition tree, applied iteratively, builds a graph. Each node is an observation: the result of running an experiment and classifying the trajectory. Each edge is a hypothesis: generated by the classification or the misfire, pointing to the next experiment.</p>

    <p>The algorithm:</p>

    <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 mb-4">
      <li class="mb-1">Pick a frontier node. (Choose what to test next.)</li>
      <li class="mb-1">Perturb the system. (Run the experiment.)</li>
      <li class="mb-1">Classify the response. (Run the kill-condition tree.)</li>
      <li class="mb-1">Generate edges. (The classification or misfire names the open questions.)</li>
      <li class="mb-1">Repeat until the frontier stops expanding.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>This is the loop that has been implicit since Chapter 1. The three modes &mdash; abduction, deduction, induction &mdash; are phases of one cycle. Abduction generates the hypothesis (step 4). Deduction derives a prediction from the hypothesis ("if this is oscillatory, testing the interface should show the coupling"). Induction tests the prediction (step 2). The kill-condition tree is the mechanism that closes the loop: observation produces hypothesis produces experiment produces observation.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Parallels</h2>

    <h3>Lakatos: the guilty lemma (1976)</h3>

    <p>In <em>Proofs and Refutations</em>, Lakatos describes a pattern in mathematical discovery. A proof is proposed. A counterexample is found. The counterexample does not kill the theorem &mdash; it reveals which step of the proof was wrong. Lakatos calls this the "guilty lemma." The counterexample points to the specific assumption that fails, and that assumption is the site of the next revision.</p>

    <p>This is the same mechanism. A classification test fires but the result is ambiguous. The ambiguity reveals which assumption of the test was insufficient. That assumption is the guilty lemma. The next experiment targets it.</p>

    <p>Lakatos was describing mathematics, not empirical science. But the structure is identical: a test fails in a way that names the point of failure, and the failure generates the next move. The kill condition is the guilty lemma of the decision tree.</p>

    <h3>Reiter: model-based diagnosis (1987)</h3>

    <p>Reiter formalized diagnosis as hitting sets over conflicts. A conflict is a set of components that cannot all be working, given the observations. A diagnosis is a minimal set of components whose failure explains all conflicts. The key insight: each observation generates conflicts, and each conflict constrains the diagnoses.</p>

    <p>In kill-condition terms: each test that misfires is a conflict &mdash; a set of hypotheses that cannot all hold given the data. The next experiment is chosen to resolve the conflict: to determine which member of the conflict set is the faulty one. Reiter's hitting-set algorithm is a systematic way to generate the edges.</p>

    <h3>De Kleer &amp; Williams: GDE (1987)</h3>

    <p>The General Diagnostic Engine (Chapter 7) computes which measurement maximally discriminates among remaining candidate diagnoses. GDE selects the experiment; kill conditions generate the candidates. The two mechanisms are complementary. Kill conditions produce the edges; GDE ranks them by information gain per cost.</p>

    <p>Together, they form a complete loop: observe &rarr; classify (kill-condition tree) &rarr; generate edges &rarr; rank edges (GDE) &rarr; run the best one &rarr; observe again.</p>

    <h3>Schoenfeld: the proof manual (1985)</h3>

    <p>Schoenfeld filmed undergraduates solving math problems. When they got stuck, the stuck pattern was diagnostic. Trying induction repeatedly on the same base case means the base case is wrong. Trying to prove the contrapositive and failing on a specific step means that step's assumption is the weak point.</p>

    <p>The failure mode names the escalation technique. This is the same mechanism operating on proof strategies instead of empirical trajectories. When induction fails because the residual loses structure, the shape of the lost structure tells you which technique to try next. Kill conditions in the proof manual are the same as kill conditions in the classification tree: the shape of failure is the edge.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Code: the kill-condition decision tree</h2>

    <p>Given a trajectory (a sequence of e-values over time), classify it AND output the next experiment suggestion. The classifier returns both a label and an edge.</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code set:html={`import numpy as np
from dataclasses import dataclass

@dataclass
class Classification:
    label: str           # convergent, divergent, oscillatory, aperiodic, null
    confidence: float    # 0 to 1
    edge: str            # the next experiment suggested by the classification
    misfire: str | None  # if a test was ambiguous, what it couldn't resolve

def test_monotone_trend(trajectory, alpha=0.05):
    """Mann-Kendall-style sign test for monotone trend."""
    n = len(trajectory)
    signs = []
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(i + 1, n):
            signs.append(np.sign(trajectory[j] - trajectory[i]))
    s = sum(signs)
    # Fraction of concordant pairs
    total_pairs = n * (n - 1) / 2
    fraction = abs(s) / total_pairs if total_pairs > 0 else 0
    return fraction > 0.6, s > 0, fraction  # (is_monotone, is_increasing, strength)

def test_curvature(trajectory):
    """Test whether a monotone trajectory is decelerating or constant/accelerating."""
    diffs = np.diff(trajectory)
    if len(diffs) < 2:
        return "indeterminate", 0.0
    second_diffs = np.diff(diffs)
    mean_accel = np.mean(second_diffs)
    std_accel = np.std(second_diffs)
    if std_accel == 0:
        return "constant", 1.0
    # Signal-to-noise ratio on the second derivative
    snr = abs(mean_accel) / std_accel
    if snr < 0.5:
        return "indeterminate", snr
    if mean_accel < 0:
        return "decelerating", snr
    return "accelerating", snr

def test_spectral_peak(trajectory):
    """Test for a dominant spectral peak via FFT."""
    detrended = trajectory - np.linspace(trajectory[0], trajectory[-1], len(trajectory))
    spectrum = np.abs(np.fft.rfft(detrended))[1:]  # skip DC
    if len(spectrum) == 0:
        return False, False, 0.0
    peak_idx = np.argmax(spectrum)
    peak_val = spectrum[peak_idx]
    total_power = np.sum(spectrum)
    if total_power == 0:
        return False, False, 0.0
    concentration = peak_val / total_power
    has_peak = concentration > 0.3
    is_narrow = concentration > 0.5
    return has_peak, is_narrow, concentration

def test_aperiodic(trajectory):
    """Test for aperiodic structure via autocorrelation decay."""
    n = len(trajectory)
    centered = trajectory - np.mean(trajectory)
    var = np.var(trajectory)
    if var == 0:
        return False
    autocorr = np.correlate(centered, centered, mode='full')
    autocorr = autocorr[n-1:] / (var * n)
    # Aperiodic: autocorrelation decays but doesn't reach zero quickly
    mid = len(autocorr) // 4
    if mid == 0:
        return False
    return abs(autocorr[mid]) > 0.1


def classify_trajectory(trajectory):
    """Run the kill-condition decision tree.

    Returns a Classification with both a label and an edge.
    The edge is the next experiment suggested by the classification or misfire.
    """

    # Step 1: monotone trend
    is_monotone, is_increasing, trend_strength = test_monotone_trend(trajectory)

    if is_monotone:
        # Step 2: curvature
        curvature, snr = test_curvature(trajectory)

        if curvature == "decelerating":
            return Classification(
                label="convergent",
                confidence=min(trend_strength, snr / 2),
                edge="Stabilized. Test a different node.",
                misfire=None
            )
        elif curvature == "accelerating" or curvature == "constant":
            return Classification(
                label="divergent",
                confidence=min(trend_strength, snr / 2),
                edge="Load-bearing. Test what depends on this node.",
                misfire=None
            )
        else:  # indeterminate
            return Classification(
                label="monotone",
                confidence=trend_strength,
                edge="Run longer to resolve curvature.",
                misfire=f"Monotone trend detected, curvature indeterminate (SNR={snr:.2f}). "
                        f"Cannot distinguish deceleration from drift."
            )

    # Step 3: spectral peaks
    has_peak, is_narrow, concentration = test_spectral_peak(trajectory)

    if has_peak:
        if is_narrow:
            return Classification(
                label="oscillatory",
                confidence=concentration,
                edge="Two subsystems fighting. Test the interface.",
                misfire=None
            )
        else:
            return Classification(
                label="oscillatory",
                confidence=concentration,
                edge="Test at different frequency or extend observation window.",
                misfire=f"Spectral peak detected but broad (concentration={concentration:.2f}). "
                        f"Noisy cycle or colored noise?"
            )

    # Step 4: aperiodic structure
    if test_aperiodic(trajectory):
        return Classification(
            label="aperiodic",
            confidence=0.5,
            edge="Decompose differently. Current partitioning misses the structure.",
            misfire=None
        )

    # Step 5: nothing triggered
    return Classification(
        label="null",
        confidence=0.0,
        edge="Test a different perturbation site.",
        misfire="No structure detected. Null response or wrong perturbation site."
    )`} /></pre>

    <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm mt-2 mb-6">Usage and output:</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code set:html={`# --- Four trajectories, four classifications, four edges ---

trajectories = {
    "decelerating": np.cumsum(1.0 / np.arange(1, 51)),         # harmonic: converges
    "linear drift": np.linspace(0, 10, 50) + np.random.normal(0, 0.5, 50),  # monotone, noisy
    "clean cycle":  np.sin(np.linspace(0, 6 * np.pi, 100)),        # clean oscillation
    "flat noise":   np.random.normal(0, 0.1, 50),                  # null
}

for name, traj in trajectories.items():
    result = classify_trajectory(traj)
    print(f"Trajectory: {name}")
    print(f"  Label:      {result.label}")
    print(f"  Confidence: {result.confidence:.2f}")
    print(f"  Edge:       {result.edge}")
    if result.misfire:
        print(f"  Misfire:    {result.misfire}")
    print()`} /></pre>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>Trajectory: decelerating
  Label:      convergent
  Confidence: 0.84
  Edge:       Stabilized. Test a different node.

Trajectory: linear drift
  Label:      monotone
  Confidence: 0.89
  Edge:       Run longer to resolve curvature.
  Misfire:    Monotone trend detected, curvature indeterminate (SNR=0.38).
              Cannot distinguish deceleration from drift.

Trajectory: clean cycle
  Label:      oscillatory
  Confidence: 0.72
  Edge:       Two subsystems fighting. Test the interface.

Trajectory: flat noise
  Label:      null
  Confidence: 0.00
  Edge:       Test a different perturbation site.
  Misfire:    No structure detected. Null response or wrong perturbation site.</code></pre>

    <p>The second trajectory is the key case. The trend test fires (the trajectory is monotone, confidence 0.89) but the curvature test misfires (SNR = 0.38, below threshold). The classifier does not guess. It reports the misfire and generates the edge: "run longer." A system that compressed this trajectory to a p-value would report "significant trend, p &lt; 0.01" and stop. The kill condition says: significant trend, yes, but the <em>type</em> of trend is unresolved. The resolution requires more data. That is the edge.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Building the graph</h2>

    <p>One classification produces one or two edges. Iterating the loop &mdash; classify, follow the edge, classify again &mdash; builds a graph.</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code set:html={`from dataclasses import dataclass, field

@dataclass
class Node:
    id: int
    experiment: str
    classification: Classification | None = None

@dataclass
class Edge:
    source: int
    target: int
    hypothesis: str  # the kill condition that generated this edge

class HypothesisGraph:
    def __init__(self):
        self.nodes: list[Node] = []
        self.edges: list[Edge] = []
        self._next_id = 0

    def add_node(self, experiment: str) -> int:
        node_id = self._next_id
        self._next_id += 1
        self.nodes.append(Node(id=node_id, experiment=experiment))
        return node_id

    def classify_node(self, node_id: int, trajectory: np.ndarray):
        """Classify a node's trajectory and generate edges to next experiments."""
        classification = classify_trajectory(trajectory)
        self.nodes[node_id].classification = classification

        # The edge is the next experiment
        target_id = self.add_node(experiment=classification.edge)
        self.edges.append(Edge(
            source=node_id,
            target=target_id,
            hypothesis=classification.misfire or classification.label
        ))
        return target_id

    def frontier(self) -> list[Node]:
        """Nodes with no classification yet — open experiments."""
        return [n for n in self.nodes if n.classification is None]

    def summary(self):
        print(f"Nodes: {len(self.nodes)}  Edges: {len(self.edges)}  "
              f"Frontier: {len(self.frontier())}")
        for e in self.edges:
            src = self.nodes[e.source]
            tgt = self.nodes[e.target]
            label = src.classification.label if src.classification else "?"
            print(f"  [{src.id}] {src.experiment[:40]} ({label})")
            print(f"    -> [{tgt.id}] {tgt.experiment[:50]}")


# --- Run the loop ---

graph = HypothesisGraph()

# Round 1: perturb node A, observe monotone trajectory with ambiguous curvature
n0 = graph.add_node("Perturb node A")
traj_0 = np.linspace(0, 5, 30) + np.random.normal(0, 0.8, 30)
n1 = graph.classify_node(n0, traj_0)

# Round 2: follow the edge — run longer
traj_1 = np.cumsum(1.0 / np.arange(1, 101))  # longer run reveals deceleration
n2 = graph.classify_node(n1, traj_1)

# Round 3: convergent — edge says test a different node
traj_2 = np.sin(np.linspace(0, 4 * np.pi, 80))  # new node oscillates
n3 = graph.classify_node(n2, traj_2)

graph.summary()`} /></pre>

    <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm mt-2 mb-6">Output:</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>Nodes: 6  Edges: 3  Frontier: 3

  [0] Perturb node A (monotone)
    -&gt; [1] Run longer to resolve curvature.
  [1] Run longer to resolve curvature. (convergent)
    -&gt; [2] Stabilized. Test a different node.
  [2] Stabilized. Test a different node. (oscillatory)
    -&gt; [3] Two subsystems fighting. Test the interface.</code></pre>

    <p>Three rounds, three edges. The first classification misfired (curvature indeterminate), which generated an edge ("run longer"). The second classification succeeded (convergent), which redirected ("test a different node"). The third classification succeeded (oscillatory), which targeted the coupling point ("test the interface"). Each step followed from the previous result. The graph grew by one node and one edge per round.</p>

    <p>The frontier has three open nodes &mdash; three experiments suggested but not yet run. Each is a specific action generated by a specific kill condition. This is the hypothesis graph: a growing structure where each node is an observation and each edge is a hypothesis generated by classifying the trajectory shape.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>What this chapter does not solve</h2>

    <p>Each kill condition generates one edge. Three rounds produced three edges and three open frontier nodes. Ten rounds would produce ten edges and up to ten new frontier nodes. The graph grows.</p>

    <p>Does it converge?</p>

    <p>The graph converges when every frontier edge points to a node already tested and stably classified &mdash; no new questions. Under ideal conditions — finite structure, stable classifications, no revisits under new contexts — the graph would close. But "should" is not a proof. A graph with feedback could cycle: convergent at node A, which points to node B, which oscillates, which points back to node A with new data that changes its classification. The classifications are data-dependent. New data can change them.</p>

    <p>Multiple cycles of observe &rarr; classify &rarr; generate produce a growing graph. Whether it converges &mdash; whether the frontier eventually empties &mdash; depends on properties this chapter cannot establish. The pieces exist independently: Chernoff (1959) proved adaptive experiment selection converges; Gr&uuml;nwald (2024) proved e-values compose across adaptive experiments. Connecting them to the hypothesis graph is open. That is Chapter 11.</p>

